\begin_layout Standard
The four steps to dynamically assign an IP address to the laptop are: DHCP
 Discover, DHCP Offer, DHCP Request, and DHCP ACK.
 The client in a DHCP conversation is given the port number 68, and the
 server is given port number 67.
 In the first step the host (laptop) broadcasts a DHCP Discover message
 to all machines on the network.
 Then, the server responds with a DHCP Offer message.
 This is also broadcast to the entire network as the laptop does not have
 an IP address yet.
 Then the host requests an IP address using the DHCP Request message broadcast
 to the network.
 Then the server sends back with the IP address using a DHCP ACK message
 broadcast.
 Every message in a DHCP conversation contains a transaction ID, to prevent
 retransmission errors and to keep track of the conversation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The laptop will have the IP address for 10 days, as that is the value of
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

IP Address Lease Time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 field in the DHCP ACK message.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DHCP protocol also provides:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Address of the first-hop router for client to allow the client to make requests
 to hosts outside of the local network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Name and IP address of DNS server to allow the client to retrieve IP information
 about websites.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Network mask tells the client how many bits of the ip addresses are for
 hosts and subnets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
our ip address is 192.168.178.103
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Some networks are set up to automatically recognise specific devices by
 their MAC address, and always assign them the same IP address.
 State whether this is the case here, and justify your answer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It appears that this network does assign the same IP address to a specific
 MAC address, as after the DHCP release message, the same IP address is
 offered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
b)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The DNS is a distributed hierarchical database with, root name servers,
 top-level domain servers and authoritative DNS servers.
 Consider the scenario where the IP address for weather.geek.nz was needed
 by a host but the name is not cached in the local DNS name server.
 Discuss the recursive solution where the IP address for weather.geek.nz would
 be retrieved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The local DNS server would then contact the root DNS server, which would
 give back information about which top-level domain server to query.
 The process would repeat again, retrievin information about the authoritative
 DNS server.
 Once this server is queried, it will return the IP address for weather.geek.nz
\end_layout

