\begin_layout Subsection*
b) need to pad this out (4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using your answers in Question 3(a) explain why routers have forwarding
 tables, and the concept of route aggregation in a forwarding table.
 Your answer should be about 150 words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Route aggregation: combining of multiple smaller prefixes into larger ones.
 This allows more efficient advertisement of routing information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Routers have forwarding tables to allow for fast and efficient routing of
 packets.
 This process needs to be done quickly to prevent queueing at the router.
 Each packet that is seen by the router is passed onto other routers via
 the forwarding table.
 These forwarding tables match IP addresses to certain outputs and are computed
 using routing algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c) (1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No, as the packets sent using TCP may be lost or retransmitted, layer 4
 still needs to handle out-of-order data.
 Layer 3 ensures that packets broken down into datagrams are able to be
 reassembled in the correct order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
4 - mild
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
a) (2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use TCP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data is guaranteed to be delivered to the client, as TCP automatically retransmi
ts packets.
 This is more reliable than UDP and ensures all the data is collected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data is guaranteed to be delivered to the receiver with no errors as TCP
 checks for errors.
 This allows for lower effort on the application layer dealing with errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The arrival of data using TCP will be in order, so the application layer
 will not need to handle out of order images.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
TCP allows for graceful shutdown of the connection between sender and receiver,
 so they know when the connection has been terminated.
\end_layout

