\begin_layout Standard
NAT is network address translation.
 This method allows a local network to only use one external IP address.
 The IP addresses of devices on the local network are not visible to the
 external hosts and are not explicitly addressable.
 This violates the end to end argument as external hosts are not talking
 directly with hosts within a NAT network.
 Instead, they talk through an intermediary NAT router, which interferes
 in the conversation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
c) (3) - needs to be fixed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pasted2.png

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the subnet mask takes 20 bits and an IP address has 32 bits.
 This leaves 12 bits for hosts on the network.
 Therefore, there can be a maximum of 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{12}=4096$
\end_inset

 hosts.
 The maximum amount if 20 hosts were routers is 4076 hosts as each router
 has an IP address.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
d) (2) - unsure, what about ip and port number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The requests are sent through the same socket of the DNS server.
 They are distinguished by their unique identification numbers.
 Each query and reply pair have the same identification number.
 The hosts are also identified by their ip and port numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
1 7/10 a little tough
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Drone Swarm Rescue System (DSRS) project is growing in size.
 The initial prototype, with multiple drones communicating over Wi-Fi, has
 been a huge success.
 The prototype has shown multiple drones can communicate with each other
 and build their own private network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The project has been so successful that it has attracted funding from several
 US government organisations.
 And while they like the current work, they want to open up the network
 so other organisations (e.g.
 US companies) can provide drones as part of the swarm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a requirement of the funding, other organisations need to add their own
 “sub-nets” of drones.
 These sub-nets will consist of multiple drones implementing their own network.
 But the multiple sub-nets will need to communicate with each other.
 One way to model this design is to treat each sub-net as a separate autonomous
 system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Using your knowledge of routing between autonomous systems, discuss the
 benefits and costs of using a BGP-like protocol for DSRS.
 Include details of how ICMP could be used to help diagnose problems between
 the different sub-nets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
BGP: Border Gateway Protocol.
 Inter-domain routing protocol (holds the internet together).
 Includes eBGP: obtain subnet reachability information from neighbouring
 ASes and iBGP: propagate reachability routes to other networks based on
 reachability information and policy.
 Built on top of TCP, semi-permanent connection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This allows specific drones to connect to other drone sub-nets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The specific behaviour of routing is based on policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Autonomous system routing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Allows subnet to advertise its existence to the rest of Internet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Administrative autonomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Benefits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Flexible and scalable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Flexible through the use of policies which allow administrators to configure
 behaviour of path advertisement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Complex configuration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Slow convergence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Security - opening up the system to external drones which may be malicious
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Needs load balancing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
May need to introduce a new type of drone with greater processing power
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ICMP: Internet Control Message Protocol.
 Used by hosts and routers to communicate network-level information.
 Includes error reporting and pinging.
 Network-layer above IP.
 Carried in IP datagrams.
 One of the main protocols in IP.
 Also used by tracert - get paths, lengths, and advertise this.
 Route advertisement router discovery.
 Drones unreachable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Describe what would happen if sub-nets stopped being cooperative and instead
 started focus on their own interests instead of the overall swarm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Route selection protocol for BGP might be non cooperative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prioritises own packets rather than others.
\end_layout

