\begin_layout Standard
Now that the DSRS project is expanding, security has become an important
 issue.
 The various funders are requiring that the drones in the swarm are secure
 and that an outside hacker would not be able to either observe what is
 happening in the swarm or take over any drones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To meet the funders’ requirements, the lead designers in the DSRS have decided
 to implement a multiple level security system.
 They desire all messages in the system to be confidential and authenticated,
 while ensuring that the services are always available.
 Knowing the risks of implementing their own protocols, they have decided
 to use pre-existing protocols, including SSL and public key cryptography.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the multiple level approach, the designers have decided to split the
 network into three security zones.
 The first zone will contain all the drones (both relay and search) and
 allow free communications between them.
 The second zone will contain the operators and allow two-way communications
 between the drones and operators.
 The third zone will be a public zone that only allows one-way traffic out
 from the operator zone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The designers want to ensure that each zone is secure and only allows the
 authorised traffic between the different zones.
 However, given they have complete control over the networks protocols in
 the network, they are sure they can lock down the network while still allowing
 normal operation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Using your knowledge of SSL and operational security, describe how the three
 zones could be configured and what additional infrastructure would be required.
 Include details of the data flows between the three zones and how each
 data flow would be secured.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
SSL: Secure Sockets Layer.
 Widely deployed security protocol.
 Provides confidentiality, integrity, authentication.
 Available to all TCP applications.
 Between the App and Transport Layers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
For your design, discuss what the potential costs would be and how they
 would impact the network performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cost of certificate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
