\begin_layout Standard
The drones in DSRS have a number of sensors and actuators that allow the
 operators to both perceive and interact with the world.
 These sensors include microphones, videos and speakers.
 Given the DSRS system allows manoeuvring drones close to people who need
 rescuing, the project sponsors have decided the system could also be useful
 for communicating with these people.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To meet the project sponsors’ requests, the designers have decided to implement
 functionality that would allow for a conversation between an operator and
 another person via a drone.
 As the operator could be operating multiple drones, they need to be able
 to switch between multiple conversations or merge multiple conversations
 into a single conference conversation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Using your knowledge of multimedia networking, discuss what issues need
 to be considered implementing the conversation functionality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What issues need to be considered implementing the conversation functionality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Latency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bandwidth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Audio, or Audio+Video, or text
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Describe how RTP and RTCP could be used to handle the requirements for multiple
 conversations and changing between conversations.

\series default
 
\series bold
Include details on how the functionality could handle missing or delayed
 data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RTP: Real-Time Protocol.
 Runs in end systems.
 Packet strucute for packets containing audio and video data.
 Encapsulated in UDP segements.
 Interoperability: if two VoIP apps run TYP, they are able to work together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RTCP: Real-Time Control Protocol.
 Works in conjunction with RTP.
 
\end_layout

